ODE IX.

Ligurinus was a handsome young man, who was so weak as to be vain of his beauty. He lost all the advantages which na·- ture had bestowed upon him by his ridiculous vanity 3 which Horace attempts to correct by reminding him that all his per— sonal attractions will soon fall a prey to time and age.

This ode is written in a playful, familiar manner to invite virgil to join a party of pleasure, at which, it would· seem, that each individua] was expected to produce something to- wards the entertainment.
